08216nam a22013095i 9781853599736DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20072007enk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818535997367 a10.21832/97818535997362doi  a(DE-B1597)513556  a(OCoLC)1078914218  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST 4aRC423b.C6427 2007 7aMED0070002bisacsh04a362.196/855a616.85500aCommunication Disorders in Spanish Speakers :bTheoretical, Research and Clinical Aspects /ced. by José G. Centeno, Raquel T. Anderson, Loraine K. Obler. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCommunication Disorders Across Languages0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpanish speakers, whether in monolingual or bilingual situations, or in majority or minority contexts, represent a considerable population worldwide. Spanish speakers in the U.S. constitute an illustrative context of the challenges faced by speech-language practitioners to provide realistic services to an increasing and diverse Spanish-speaking caseload. There is still considerable paucity in the amount of literature on Hispanic individuals with clinical relevance in speech-language pathology. Particularly lacking are works that link both empirical and theoretical bases to evidence-based procedures for child and adult Spanish users with communication disorders. Further, because communication skills depend on multiple phenomena beyond strictly linguistic factors, speech-language students and practitioners require multidisciplinary bases to realistically understand Spanish clients’ communication performance. This volume attempts to address those gaps. This publication takes a multidisciplinary approach that integrates both theoretical and empirical grounds from Speech-Language Pathology, Neurolinguistics, Neuropsychology, Education, and Clinical Psychology to develop evidence-based clinical procedures for monolingual Spanish and bilingual Spanish-English children and adults with communication disorders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aAméricains d'origine latino-américainexLangagexUnited States. 0aAnglais (Langue)xAcquisition. 0aBilingualism in childrenxUnited States. 0aBilingualism in childrenzUnited States. 0aBilingualismxPhysiological aspects. 0aBilingualismxUnited States. 0aBilingualismzUnited States. 0aBilinguisme chez l'enfantxÉtats-Unis. 0aBilinguismexÉtats-Unis. 0aCommunication, Troubles de laxTraitementxÉtats-Unis. 0aCommunication, Troubles de la, chez l'enfantxTraitementxÉtats-Unis. 0aCommunicative disorders in childrenxTreatmentxUnited States. 0aCommunicative disorders in childrenxTreatmentzUnited States. 0aCommunicative disordersxTreatmentxUnited States. 0aCommunicative disordersxTreatmentzUnited States. 0aEnglish languagexAcquisition. 0aEspagnol (Langue)xAcquisition. 0aHispanic American childrenxLanguage. 0aHispanic AmericansxLanguage. 0aSpanish languagexAcquisition. 7aMEDICAL / Audiology & Speech Pathology.2bisacsh  aCommunication disorders.  aHispanic.  aNeurolinguistics.  aSpain.  aspeech-language pathology.1 aAnderson, Raquel T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Raquel T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAnsaldo, Ana Inés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArdila, Alfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell-Berti, Fredericka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrozgold, Alizah Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 